    {
      "title": "Equation of chord of contact",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>The equation of chord of contact</h3><p>If from $\\text{P}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ tangents $\\text{PA}$ and $\\text{PB}$ are drawn to the parabola ${{\\text{y}}^{2}}=4\\text{ax}$ then equation of chord of contact $\\text{AB}$ is $\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}=2\\mathbf{a}\\left( \\text{x}+{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)$ which follows from the fact that the equation which is being claimed to be equation of $\\text{AB}$ represents a line and is satisfied by co-ordinates of $A$ and $B$. Indeed if $A$ be $\\left( \\alpha ,\\beta \\right)$ then $\\text{AP}$ is tangent at $\\text{P}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"224\" height=\"193\"></p><p>$\\Rightarrow $ Equation of $\\text{AP}$ is $\\text{y}\\beta =2\\text{a}\\left( \\text{x}+\\alpha \\right)$</p><p>Since it passes through $\\text{P}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ we must have</p><p>$\\beta {{\\text{y}}_{1}}=2\\text{a}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\alpha \\right)$</p><p>which shows that the point $\\text{A}\\left( \\alpha ,\\beta \\right)$ lies on the line</p><p>$\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}=2\\text{a}\\left( \\text{x}+{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)$</p><p>Similarly the point B lies on the line $\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}=2\\text{a}\\left( \\text{x}+{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)$ which completes the proof.</p><p><strong>NOTE :&nbsp;</strong></p><p>The equation of chord of contact resembles with that of the tangent's equation but in the tangent's case the point $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ lies on the parabola.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd57c03b9dcaf1afea7b"
    }
